21) Script to check if a number is even or odd 

set -euo pipefail

read -r -p "Enter an integer: " n
re='^-?[0-9]+$'
[[ $n =~ $re ]] || { echo "Not an integer"; exit 1; }

if (( n % 2 == 0 )); then
  echo "$n is even"
else
  echo "$n is odd"
fi
________________________________________
22) Difference between if and case in bash 
Feature	if statement	case statement
Use	Numeric or string comparison using conditions	Pattern matching (wildcards, strings)
Syntax	if [ condition ]; then ... elif ... else ... fi	case value in pattern) commands;; *) default;; esac
Flexibility	Handles complex logic (>, <, &&, `	
Example	bash if [[ $x -gt 10 ]]; then echo big; fi	bash case $x in 10) echo ten;; 20) echo twenty;; esac
________________________________________
23) Script to find largest of three numbers 
#!/usr/bin/env bash
set -euo pipefail

read -r -p "Enter first number: " a
read -r -p "Enter second number: " b
read -r -p "Enter third number: " c

if (( a >= b && a >= c )); then
  echo "$a is largest"
elif (( b >= a && b >= c )); then
  echo "$b is largest"
else
  echo "$c is largest"
fi
________________________________________
24) For loop to traverse array
Bash treats commas as characters, so correct definition removes them.
#!/usr/bin/env bash
set -euo pipefail

arr=(123 "Abs" -2.3 'A' 23.56 0)

echo "Elements in array:"
for element in "${arr[@]}"; do
  echo "$element"
done
________________________________________
25) Loop through all files in current directory 
#!/usr/bin/env bash
set -euo pipefail

for file in *; do
  [[ -f "$file" ]] && echo "File: $file"
done
________________________________________
26) Difference between while and until loops (CO4)
Feature	while loop	until loop
Execution condition	Runs while the condition is true	Runs until the condition becomes true
Logical opposite	True means continue	True means stop
Example	bash while [[ $x -lt 5 ]]; do ((x++)); done	bash until [[ $x -ge 5 ]]; do ((x++)); done
________________________________________
27) Countdown timer using while loop 
#!/usr/bin/env bash
set -euo pipefail

read -r -p "Enter seconds to count down: " t
while (( t > 0 )); do
  echo -ne "Time left: $t sec\r"
  sleep 1
  ((t--))
done
echo -e "\nTime's up!"
________________________________________
28) Using break and continue
#!/usr/bin/env bash
set -euo pipefail

for i in {1..10}; do
  if (( i == 5 )); then
    echo "Skipping $i"
    continue
  fi
  if (( i == 8 )); then
    echo "Breaking at $i"
    break
  fi
  echo "Count: $i"
done
continue skips current iteration; break exits the loop entirely.

29) Check if a file exists or not
#!/usr/bin/env bash
set -euo pipefail

read -r -p "Enter filename: " fname

if [[ -f "$fname" ]]; then
  echo "File exists."
else
  echo "File does not exist."
fi
